From 6148b1a62759aea9a731f77a80646c7315870734 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Daniel Morandini <danielmorandini@me.com>
Date: Mon, 29 Jun 2026 12:02:14 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] fftools/ffmpeg_demux: per-stream copyts MPEG-TS wrap
 continuation

libavformat's wrap_timestamp() only adds at most one PTS epoch and stops
once raw timestamps climb back past pts_wrap_reference, so under -copyts
a long-running MPEG-TS input regresses its dts by 2^33 at the 33-bit
wrap. The previous handling detected this for audio/video and folded the
correction into the shared Demuxer.ts_offset_discont. That global offset
has two failure modes: it diverges when audio and video cross the wrap on
different packets (starving the interleaver), and it never reaches sparse
stream-copied data (SCTE-35) or subtitle/teletext PIDs, whose regressed
dts then reaches the muxer -- clamped for subtitles, fatal for data.

Track the wrap per stream instead. Each DemuxStream accumulates its own
wrap_offset; a fresh rollover is detected as a backward dts step of more
than half a wrap versus that stream's previous raw dts, and adds the
nearest integer number of wrap periods. Detection keys on dts only
(monotonic by construction, unlike B-frame pts) and the same delta is
applied to pts and dts, preserving ordering and delay. This keeps every
timeline monotonic and independent, fixing both the audio/video
starvation and the copied-stream regression with a single mechanism, and
removes the global-offset wrap path under -copyts entirely. Adding an
exact multiple of 2^33 is wrap-correct for the MPEG-TS muxer, which masks
pts/dts/pcr back to 33 bits on the wire.

Add an in-tree synthetic fixture generator (tests/mpegtswrapgen) and FATE
regression tests asserting monotonic copied DTS across one and multiple
wraps for subtitle, DVB teletext and SCTE-35 streams. Without the fix the
SCTE cases abort ffmpeg and the subtitle/teletext cases clamp the
post-wrap DTS.

